<h1>New models in research and courseware publishing</h1>
<a href="/">Home</a>-<a href="/blog/index.html">blog</a>-<a href="/blog/2005/index.html">2005</a>-<a href="/blog/2005/05/index.html">05</a>-<a href="/blog/2005/05/05/index.html">05</a>
<p>
Peter Albion of USQ proposed an intriguing model of publishing in a conversation we had some time ago. I prompted him to <a class="external" href="http://edux.usq.edu.au/~albion/weblog/index.php?p=51">write it up</a>. Peter notes that USQ's current courseware dilutes authorship as a course is revised over time, and the rewards of writing coursware are less than for writing research paper. He proposes a new model in which indivdiual academics would publish, and courses would be constructed out of those published materials.</p>
